{
  "success": true,
  "query": "engineering AI health dashboard monitoring",
  "results": [
    {
      "layer": 1,
      "layer_name": "Domain Knowledge (This Company)",
      "header": "AI Health Dashboard (Feb 10, 2026)",
      "content": "## AI Health Dashboard (Feb 10, 2026)\n- **Route**: `/admin/ai-health` (session-protected) — 10 module cards + 7 AI modality cards + 11 AI module rows + call distribution\n- **Tabs**: Overview (cards), Status (health banner, 12 stat cards, DB pool gauge, slow queries, token budget per-provider, activity feed), Metrics (CPU/memory/DB/API latency percentiles), Activity Feed (60+ route patterns auto-categorized, 208+ logged, color-coded)\n- **Backend collectors**: `db.js` (query tracking, pool %), `metrics-collector.js` (HTTP connections), `token-budget.js` (per-provider), `server.js` (HTTP connection tracking)",
      "relevance": "102%"
    },
    {
      "layer": 3,
      "layer_name": "Cross-Company Patterns",
      "header": "Deployment & Infrastructure",
      "content": "### Deployment & Infrastructure\n- Stack: Express + PostgreSQL/Neon, deployed on Render\n- Port 10000 standard for Express servers on Render\n- **Render health check endpoint**: Must serve `/health` (not `/api/health`); failed health checks cause silent rollback to previous deploy; place health route at TOP of server.js BEFORE all middleware to ensure instant 200 response without falling through to 404 handler; both `/health` and `/api/health` can coexist; enhanced health endpoint tests database connectivity and returns 503 when services degraded; support optional query param `?check=db` to return 503 if database connection fails\n- **Trust proxy for rate limiting AND session cookies**: Add `app.set('trust proxy', 1)` immediately after Express app creation, before any middleware; tells Express to trust X-Forwarded-For header from load balancer; rate limiting then sees actual client IPs instead of proxy IP; value `1` means \"trust exactly one proxy hop\" — correct for Render's single load balancer layer; CRITICAL for session cookie security: Render terminates SSL at load balancer, so Express sees HTTP without this setting, refuses to set `Secure` cookie flag, browser rejects insecure session cookie, user stays logged out despite successful auth → perpetual 401 redirect loops\n- **Session persistence before response**: Use explicit `req.session.save(callback)` in auth routes (signup, login) to guarantee session persists to PostgreSQL before HTTP response sends; prevents race condition where cookie set but database write still pending when browser receives response\n- **Render build script requirement**: package.json must include \"build\" script; Render runs `npm run build` on deploy and fails without it; script can be no-op (`\"build\": \"echo done\"`) for Node-only apps without frontend compilation\n- **Package.json dependency verification**: All `require()` statements in server.js, route files, and db connection modules must have corresponding entries in package.json dependencies; missing entries cause deploy failures even if code is syntactically correct; use `npm install [package] --save` before committing code that imports new modules; previous commits may have written code referencing modules without installing them — audit git history for orphaned imports\n- Zero-downtime deploys: use deferred FK constraints, avoid schema locks during migration\n- Chunked uploads (5MB) for Render's body-size limit\n- Blocked platforms: Reddit, Medium, Twitter (all 403)\n- **Service worker caching chain failures**: Three-layer cache system (browser + service worker + server headers) can break when: (1) express.static() serves HTML before custom no-cache routes execute (route ordering bug), (2) service worker uses cache-first strategy for HTML instead of network-first, (3) service worker file itself has no cache-busting headers; fix requires: route reordering to prioritize no-cache endpoints, network-first strategy for HTML assets, cache version bumps (e.g., `atomency-v3`), cache-busting params on service worker (`?v=timestamp`), and explicit `Pragma: no-cache, Expires: 0` headers; users see stale content despite successful deploys until hard refresh (Ctrl+Shift+R); two-minute window after fix where old service worker still active; subsequent deploys become visible immediately after service worker update installed\n- **Deploy verification pattern**: Wait 2-3 min post-deploy, curl endpoints to confirm old code gone, verify new features live before marking task complete\n- **Deploy status lag on Render**: `build_in_progress` status may persist >8 min despite successful build logs; wait 5+ min, then trigger manual re-deploy if stuck; verify file size/content changes via curl before assuming stale cache; app logs empty until build completes and app starts\n- **Stale static asset verification**: Check `Content-Length` and `Last-Modified` headers to confirm new assets served; size change confirms fresh deployment\n- **Custom domain infrastructure requirements**: Domain must be registered on Render service as PREREQUISITE for SSL cert provisioning; DNS resolution alone insufficient; code-level middleware cannot bypass SSL handshake failures; if domain not registered on Render, every connection attempt fails with `ERR_SSL_VERSION_OR_CIPHER_MISMATCH` regardless of code changes; domain registration via Render dashboard is 30-second action, auto-provisions Let's Encrypt cert in ~2 minutes\n- **Custom domain DNS misconfiguration detection**: GoDaddy domain forwarding feature overwrites A records with forwarding server IPs instead of letting you point to hosting provider; disable forwarding entirely, configure A record to point to hosting provider's IP (e.g., Render load balancer), add www CNAME to subdomain; absence of www DNS record causes broken redirect chains\n- **Environment variable changes on Render**: Setting/updating env vars via dashboard OR update_env_vars tool automatically triggers redeploy; service restarts to pick up new values; no manual deploy trigger needed; changes live in 1-2 minutes",
      "relevance": "73%"
    },
    {
      "layer": 3,
      "layer_name": "Cross-Company Patterns",
      "header": "Current Cross-Company Patterns (engineering) (9847 tokens)",
      "content": "## Current Cross-Company Patterns (engineering) (9847 tokens)",
      "relevance": "33%"
    },
    {
      "layer": 3,
      "layer_name": "Cross-Company Patterns",
      "header": "Middleware & Routing",
      "content": "### Middleware & Routing\n- **Middleware execution order matters**: API routes BEFORE `express.static()` ensures middleware runs on static files; health route must be FIRST to bypass all middleware; explicit route handlers must come BEFORE `express.static()` so routes take priority over static file serving; custom no-cache routes for HTML must execute BEFORE `express.static()` serves cached fallback; tracking middleware must run BEFORE static routes to capture all page views; operational/admin endpoints with token auth (e.g., `/ops/*`) should bypass session/CSRF/rate-limit middleware via explicit conditional skip before middleware assignment\n- **Route ordering for parameterized routes**: Move specific routes (e.g., `/dashboard/stats`) BEFORE parameterized routes (e.g., `/:id`); Express matches top-to-bottom, so `GET /:id` catches `GET /dashboard` if ordered incorrectly; add `isNaN()` guards on ID params with `next()` fallthrough to allow non-numeric values to skip to more specific routes\n- **Static directory serving multiple source folders**: Multiple `express.static()` calls can serve different directories at different mount points (e.g., `/ops` → `ops/`, `/public` → `public/`); first matching handler serves the file; allows separation of operational output files from user-facing content\n- **Singular vs plural URL forms**: Route definitions use specific forms (e.g., `/tool/:slug` singular); requests to plural forms (`/tools/:slug`) return 404; add 301 redirect middleware from plural to singular form to support both URL patterns\n- **Modular route architecture — route-based separation for coexisting apps**: When multiple distinct applications must coexist on same deployment without overwriting each other, split functionality into separate route files and mount via `app.use()` with distinct base paths (e.g., `/newsletter`, `/brief`); each app gets own landing page, API endpoints, environment variable configs, and branding; each route file exports factory function accepting `(pool, middleware, config, utilities)` as parameters; reduces main server.js size; improves maintainability",
      "relevance": "32%"
    },
    {
      "layer": 1,
      "layer_name": "Domain Knowledge (This Company)",
      "header": "Route Mounting (server.js)",
      "content": "## Route Mounting (server.js)\n`/api/auth`, `/api/jobs`, `/api/interviews`, `/api/omniscore`, `/api/candidate`, `/api/assessments`, `/api/company`, `/api/trustscore`, `/api/recruiter`, `/api/matching`, `/api/documents`, `/api/payroll`, `/api/compliance`, `/api/onboarding`, `/api/analytics`, `/api/countries`, `/api/ai-health` | Admin: `/admin/login`, `/admin/logout`, `/admin/ai-health`",
      "relevance": "23%"
    }
  ]
}

